Virtual Applications are just like your website, It is a group of files that provides services over protocols, it uses its own scripting or AppPool, It has all the options of a website. but also acts as a virtual directory letting you place the directory path outside the website root.

Virtual Applications (Virtual Web Mappings) are just like your CF website,A virtual web mapping lets you map a physical system path to a logical resource path that might be outside the ColdFusion MX web root. For example, you might want to map the physical directory "\resources\images" to the logical resource path /images. After setting up the mapping, users access the directory using a URL in the following form: http://hostname/images/. One advantage to using virtual web mappings is that it hides the physical layout of your application directory structure from users. This can aslo be used to run seperate apps within your CF application.

Note: These mappings are independent of ColdFusion virtual directories. If you would like to create a virtual directory to access a given directory through a URL, please consult your ColdFusion Documentation. Virtual Directories are just a pointer to the directory path so the directory path is not accessible from the web using the original directory name, This is good for many reasons, 1. Use a directory outside the path of the website. 2. Directory Names, so if your directory is named Files_reports_Store_Sales you can name your VD SalesReports and it will render the content in your directory it is pointing to.

Note: These mappings are independent of FrontPage virtual directories. If you would like to create a virtual directory to access a given directory through a URL, please consult your FrontPage Documentation. After creating your virtual directory go to FP administrator and create a subweb with the SAME name as virtual directory is. ie: IIS Root C:\IISROOT\WWW, Application File location \\SOMESYSTEM\SHARED_DISK, Assuming we want the application accessed as HTTP://servername/MYAPP, For that, create virtual directory MYAPP pointing to \\SOMESYSTEM\SHARED_DISK, Make sure that that application doesn't contain existing FP extensions (if it does, delete directories _vti* in there) Then, go to FP Administrator, and create a subweb for the web site name MYAPP.
